column4: I mainly learned Japanese by immersion and self-teaching. I only had a few language courses in my life but I think they were useful. However, I can handle everyday conversation, fend for myself  alone in Japan (with some help though ^^') and I know many kanjis. This is because I spent a lot of time in this country. I first came with my parents when I was 3 for ~2 months, then I lived 10 months in the Kansai when I was 7 and went to a japanese shougakkou where I made friends, and one in particular.. I also came back several times during summer holidays, in general for 3 weeks to 2 months, at my friend's family home. Once I went to Tokyo but I am not a big city girl, I prefer Kyoto, Nara...  ^^' And my friends told me that I used the Kansai "dialect" (kansaiben)  :D Then I spent 7 months at Kyoto for my master degree internship 2 years ago... But I worked almost all the time and almost had no occasion to practice Japanese... :'( So I started working kanjis and vocabulary by myself, with apps mainly, then I started to watch animes and to take breaks regularly to note down some words or expressions or look for a kanji. I think I have an intermediate but uneven level as speaking is quite natural to me while I may lack formal knowledge in writing and reading.

Using with some friends. It's a constructed language, and it's constructed to be "situation based", vocabulary is limited and it's very good for describing "here and now" in context dependant ways. As such - I don't really like using it online in "text-only" based situations, nor do I consider translations to it really useful. Ambiguity is a feature in Toki-Pona, and I find sentences which over-describe the situation, well not flowing with the language. Not fond of coining set expressions in Toki-Pona as some speakers are. That should be again dependent of situation and speech community. Speaking Toki-Pona is also fighting the human instinct to coin set new words and phrases. I'm really happy I've learnt it, it's like a mini language learning experiments. I saw it took me 1.5 month to become comfortable with the 120-word vocab, and maybe another month of usage to really start thinking in the language.
